 summary: 'A network of international organizations, forums, and foundations influence global policy while operating outside democratic accountability. Elite groups including Bilderberg, the Council on Foreign Relations, and the Trilateral Commission coordinate positions that shape government policy across nations.',
 content: [
 'BILDERBERG MEETINGS: Since 1954, annual invitation-only conferences bring together political leaders, corporate executives, royalty, and media figures. Attendees include prime ministers, presidents, and Fortune 500 CEOs. Discussions are off-record with no public accountability. Notable attendees include Henry Kissinger, David Rockefeller, Margaret Thatcher, Bill Clinton, Tony Blair, and Angela Merkel.',
 'COUNCIL ON FOREIGN RELATIONS: The CFR, founded in 1921, shapes American foreign policy. Members include presidents, secretaries of state, and national security advisors from both parties. The organization publishes Foreign Affairs journal and produces policy recommendations that often become government policy.',
 'TRILATERAL COMMISSION: Founded in 1973 by David Rockefeller and Zbigniew Brzezinski, this group coordinates policy among North America, Europe, and Japan (now including Asia-Pacific broadly). Members have included Presidents Carter, Clinton, and Bush Sr. Critics note the democratic deficit in transnational policy coordination.',
 'DAVOS WORLD ECONOMIC FORUM: Annual gathering of 3,000+ political and business leaders. Private meetings determine global economic direction. Access requires significant fees or invitation. Policies discussed at Davos often appear in government agendas globally within months.',
 'FOUNDATION NETWORKS: The Gates Foundation, Open Society Foundations (Soros), Rockefeller Foundation, and Ford Foundation coordinate on global health, education, and governance initiatives. Their combined influence rivals nation-states while avoiding democratic oversight.',
 'ATLANTIC COUNCIL: Think tank with board including former heads of CIA, NSA, and major corporations. Shapes NATO and transatlantic policy. Closely coordinates with governments on security policy while funded by defense contractors and foreign governments.',
 'BROOKINGS & HERITAGE: Major think tanks provide personnel and policy to administrations. The revolving door between government, think tanks, and corporations creates an insular policy elite. Heritage Foundation\'s Project 2025 demonstrates pre-planned government takeover strategies.',
 'CLUB OF ROME: Founded 1968, this group of industrialists and academics promoted population control and environmental crisis narratives. The 1972"Limits to Growth"report influenced global policy. Critics argue it advocated deindustrialization affecting ordinary people while protecting elite interests.',
 'BANK FOR INTERNATIONAL SETTLEMENTS: The"central bank of central banks"coordinates global monetary policy with no public accountability. Located in Basel, Switzerland with sovereign immunity. Creates financial policy affecting billions without democratic input.',
 'WORLD HEALTH ORGANIZATION: While nominally accountable to member states, WHO funding increasingly comes from foundations (Gates is second-largest funder after US). This private influence shapes global health policy. The pandemic treaty negotiations would expand WHO authority.',
 ],
